.TH "HTMLElement.offsetLeft" "JS" "April 7, 2023" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLElement.offsetLeft \- HTMLElement: offsetLeft property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]HTMLElement.offsetLeft\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property
returns the number of pixels that the \f[I]upper left corner\f[R] of the
current element is offset to the left within the
\f[CR]HTMLElement.offsetParent\f[R] node.
.PP
For block\-level elements, \f[CR]offsetTop\f[R], \f[CR]offsetLeft\f[R],
\f[CR]offsetWidth\f[R], and \f[CR]offsetHeight\f[R] describe the border
box of an element relative to the \f[CR]offsetParent\f[R].
.PP
However, for inline\-level elements (such as \f[B]span\f[R]) that can
wrap from one line to the next, \f[CR]offsetTop\f[R] and
\f[CR]offsetLeft\f[R] describe the positions of the \f[I]first\f[R]
border box (use \f[CR]Element.getClientRects()\f[R] to get its width and
height), while \f[CR]offsetWidth\f[R] and \f[CR]offsetHeight\f[R]
describe the dimensions of the \f[I]bounding\f[R] border box (use
\f[CR]Element.getBoundingClientRect()\f[R] to get its position).
Therefore, a box with the left, top, width and height of
\f[CR]offsetLeft\f[R], \f[CR]offsetTop\f[R], \f[CR]offsetWidth\f[R] and
\f[CR]offsetHeight\f[R] will not be a bounding box for a span with
wrapped text.
.SH VALUE
An integer.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] colorTable = document.getElementById(\[dq]t1\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] tOLeft = colorTable.offsetLeft;

\f[B]if\f[R] (tOLeft > 5) {
  \f[I]// large left offset: do something here\f[R]
}
.EE
.PP
